					<div>
				<img src="data:image/svg+xml;charset=utf-8,%3Csvg xmlns%3D'http%3A%2F%2Fwww.w3.org%2F2000%2Fsvg' viewBox%3D'0 0 760 873'%2F%3E"
		data-src=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/380x437r/photos/98-29-campbell.jpg data-src-retina=https://226391-691236-raikfcquaxqncofqfm.stackpathdns.com/thumbs/760x873r/photos/98-29-campbell.jpg
	 alt="98 - Unknown - Campbell"
	 class="lazy">

							</div>
			</div>
</figure>
</p>

<p>Elizabeth Rose Campbell writes of herself that she was &ldquo;affiliated with <strong>THE SUN</strong> from 1976 to 1982 in various and sundry roles: magazine distributor, typesetter, subscriptions clerk, assistant editor, contributing editor, and flower bed manager. She was infamous for being unable to make good office coffee and being chronically 15 minutes late, but was nevertheless, much loved.</p>

<p>&ldquo;She left the Chapel Hill area in June of 1982 when she began working for Omega Institute for Holistic Studies in Rhinebeck, New York, where she is a member of the program committee that creates more than 100 workshops per summer, which are held on Omega&rsquo;s campus in Rhinebeck. She is also director of marketing.</p>

<p>&ldquo;To receive mailings (bi-monthy) of her less saleable but more interesting essays (some of them rediscovered time bombs of the past, others the fireworks of the moment), send $3.00 per month to Elizabeth Rose Campbell, P.O. Box 404, Rhinebeck, N.Y. 12572.&rdquo;</p>
														</div>


				
